We complete the square in $x$ and $y$ to get
\[(x-3)^2+(y-7)^2=1.\]Thus the center of the circle is $(3,7)$ and the radius is 1. The circle is shown below:

[asy]
size(100);
draw((0,7)--(6,7),dashed);
draw(circle((3,7),1));
label("$y=7$",(6,7),E);
label("$(3,7)$",(3,7),N);
[/asy]

The part of the circle below $y=7$ is shown in red below:

[asy]
size(100);
filldraw(arc((3,7),1,0,180)--cycle,red,black);
draw((0,7)--(6,7),dashed);
draw(circle((3,7),1));
label("$y=7$",(6,7),E);
label("$(3,7)$",(3,7),N);
[/asy]

Thus the area of the circle that lies beneath the line $y=7$ is equal to the area of the red region, which is half of the area of the entire circle.  The area of the circle is $\pi(1^2)=\pi$, so the area of the red region is $\frac{1}{2}\pi=\boxed{\frac{\pi}{2}}$.

